\begin_layout Standard
First,
 topology conditions relation.
 On your Deleuzian side,
 actualized relations are already conditioned by intensive asymmetry;
 the unequal and asymmetrical distance are positive and genetic,
 not secondary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 relation entails mediation.
 A relation that exists is not pure identity or perfect transmission;
 it requires channels,
 transformations,
 spacing,
 delay,
 and passage.
 Serres’ point is exactly that perfect relation would disappear into immediacy and cease to be observable as relation.
 Actual relation exists only as mediated relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third,
 mediation entails noise/parasitism.
 Once mediation exists,
 noise is not optional.
 Guilherme’s summary of Serres is useful here:
 messages must pass through means and modes of communication,
 and that necessarily interferes with the message;
 noise is therefore constitutive of communication.
\end_layout

