\begin_layout Section
Appended Refinement:
 Vertices as Internal Dynamical Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Why this refinement is necessary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The earlier formulation still permitted a residual simplification:
 it treated the terms at the vertices of a relation as if they were places that 
\emph on
carried
\emph default
 state,
 while the relation itself operated 
\emph on
between
\emph default
 them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is no longer sufficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a relation genuinely transforms the terms that enter into it,
 then the dynamics of the relation do not stop at the edge between nodes.
 They continue 
\emph on
inside
\emph default
 the terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that a vertex cannot be treated as a passive container.
 It must itself be understood as a local field of ongoing dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Narrative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relation penetrates the term.
 What looks like a node is really a fold of the same dynamic field from which the relation emerged.
\end_layout

